  <span id="freeText6799607186695662842" style="display:none">better: A Surgeon’s Notes on Performance<br /><br />This is another book that I picked up at a used bookstore, and so glad that I did!<br /><br />The book is divided into three parts: diligence, doing right, and ingenuity<br /><br />It’s an interesting read if you like learning more about what it’s like as a doctor, a surgeon or working in a hospital. Or just interested in knowing more about the medical profession. <br /><br />I learned that stethoscopes are notorious carriers of infection between patients.<br /><br /><br />In eighteen forty-seven a twenty-eight-year-old Viennese obstetrician figured out that by not washing hands for well enough, doctors themselves were to blame for childbed fever which was also known as Puerperal fever. The leading cause of maternal death in childbirth before antibiotics and the recognition that germs were the agents of infectious disease.<br /><br /><br />In part two I especially liked learning more about the doctors of the death chamber, about executions in prisons. <br /><br />Now to pregnancy. Once the water breaks chances that bacterial will into the uterus rises with each passing hour. <br />Surgery in ancient times was a way to save an entrapped baby. <br /><br />Caesarean section may have arisen from the tale that Caesar was born by an abdominal delivery but it is something historians regard is a myth.<br /><br />I was also shocked to learn that in the mid-1930s delivering a child had been the single most dangerous event in a woman’s life. <br />One in a hundred-and-fifty pregnancies ended in death of the mother.<br /><br />I was even more shocked to learn that many newborns born malformed or too small or just blue and not breathing well were listed as stillborn and placed out of sight and left to die. The belief being that they were too sickly to live.<br /><br />It wasn’t until Virginia Apgar an obstetrician changed all that by developing the universally no Apgar score allowing nurses to rate the condition of babies at birth on a scale from 0 to 10<br />two points for a baby being pink<br />two points for cry<br />two points for taking good, vigorous breaths<br />two points for moving all four limbs<br />two points for heart rate over a hundred<br />for enforcement a child born blue or limp could be resuscitated by oxygen and warming rising the score in the US one for oral term baby dies in one out of five hundred births a mother dies in less than one in ten thousand the stats of nineteen thirty.<br />If we went by those stats 20s seven thousand mothers would have died in a hundred sixty thousand newborns.<br /><br />It was also fascinated to learn about the history of forceps and about choosing the right type for the shape of the mother’s pelvis and the size of the child’s head. <br /><br />It was also interesting to learn about Nanded, India and the medical issues doctors faced there. <br /><br />There are just too many interesting facts and knowledge that I learned from reading this book to list them all here.<br /><br />Even though this book was published in 2007 the statistics regarding the past are still valid.<br />So if you like learning more about the medical profession and/or the history of the medical profession I recommend this book as a fascinating read.<br /></span>
